{
  "text": "overproduction. In the present study, we provide evidence that this beneficial effect can also be obtained with an arginase inhibitor. It is worth noting that recent reports reported that statins inhibit arginase activity [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] and that blockade of ANG-II AT1 receptors prevents the ANG II-induced elevation of arginase activity and expression [CITATION_3] . Although speculative, we hypothesize that arginase could be the downstream common effector of these two types of drugs. Because the deficiency of L-arginine causes a NOS uncoupling leading to O 2 -. production [CITATION_4] , the beneficial effect of arginase inhibition on O 2 -. production might be due to the decrease in vascular eNOS uncoupling, as recently demonstrated in the vasculature of aged rats treated with the arginase inhibitor 2S-amino-6-boronohexanoic acid [CITATION_5] . Additionally, since COX-2 was found to contribute to O 2 -production [CITATION_6] , the nor-NOHA-induced decrease in COX-2 activity might also contribute to this effect. Moreover, our results confirmed the deleterious impact of increased NADPH oxidase activity to endothelial function in AIA [CITATION_7] and demonstrated that nor-NOHA reverses this phenomenon. Whether arginase inhibition can directly reduce NADPH oxidase activity/expression is currently unknown but a recent study showing that NADPH oxidase inhibition reduced arginase upregulation in retinal cells [CITATION_8] suggests an interplay between the two enzymes.",
